test instructor

Universally, students thought Prof. Cadman was “amusing” and “energetic”. One student asked: “is it weird that I look forward to Accounting every week?” While it may be very difficult to make Accounting “come alive”, Prof. Cadman succeeded.  A dozen students called Prof. Cadman “the best teacher I have had at Wharton!”  “This is the quality of course I would expect from paying $40K a yea,r,” said one reviewer.  Students noted the professor’s accessibility, and willingness to meet outside of class to discuss problems.  The difficulty of the curve was noted as the only downside to the course.

Students thought Prof. Defeo was an enthusiastic and passionate teacher, even though the material isn’t naturally exciting.  The professor was “thorough” and “accessible”, but several reviewers felt that he was too repetitive.  The actual exams were “tricky”, and more difficult than the practice problems.  Students felt that the grading system did not reflect mastery of the material.

ACCT101 is an introduction to the basic concepts and standards underlying financial accounting systems. Several important concepts will, be studied in detail, including revenue recognition, inventory, long-lived assets, present value, and long term liabilities. The course emphasizes the construction of the basic financial accounting statements - the income statement, balance sheet, and cash flow statement - as well as their interpretation.

Students, for the most part, agreed that the material of this course, though boring, is useful and relevant to the real world. Many students found the class material helpful, especially from a “financial analyst’s perspective.” The course covered a great deal of material, but the required text book is “nothing less than excellent.”

While the students agreed that Professor Gordon was “clearly very knowledgeable about the course material,” they felt that she was \"unable to stimulate student interest.” Students thought that she “did not command enough respect from the class” but agreed that Professor Gordon was very “nice, friendly and helpful.” She prepares slides for the class, although they frequently contain some errors. Students note that Professor Gordon “answers all questions both in class and via email no matter how silly or irrelevant they may seem.” They also felt that Professor Gordon is very enthusiastic and approachable; one stated that “she actually, cared about the students understanding the material.” However, some students felt that Professor Gordon went through the concepts too quickly and should slow down.

Some students found the course “challenging” but felt that they “learned a lot” at the same time. They found that they did well as long as they kept up with the material. Some non-Wharton students also opted to “take this class pass/fail because it seems useful.”

The f,irst part of ACCT102 presents alternative methods of preparing managerial accounting information, and the remainder of the course examines how these methods are used by companies. Managerial accounting is a company\'s internal language and grants a thorough understanding of a company\'s internal operations. It is used for decision-making, production management, product design and pricing, and for motivating and evaluating employees.

The majority of the students felt that the material taught in this class was very boring and that the required text book for the course was convoluted and sometimes difficult to understand. They also thought that there was too little material covered and thus a great deal of repetition.

Professor Defeo, according to students, was very well informed on the course material and “tried very hard to be entertaining and engaging.” Many students noted, however, that Professor Defeo was very long-winded in his explanations and “could be a lot more concise.” Some also found that Professor Defeo was “inaccessible to discuss problems,” but others felt that he “made himself available for questions outside of class.” While students found his slides useful and comprehensive, some did not like that Professor Defeo tended to read off of his slides.

As far as difficulty is conce,rned, students did not find this course particularly challenging. For the most part, they agreed that although “exams were representative of the material covered,” they were much harder than what they had been taught in class. There is a good amount of work required for this class, including weekly assignments and homework. Most students took this course to fulfill the Wharton core requirement.

ACCT 101 is an introduction to the basic concepts and standards underlying financial accounting systems. Several important concepts will be studied in detail, including: revenue recognition, inventory, long-lived assets, present value, and long term liabilities. The course emphasizes the construction of the basic financial accounting statements – the income statement, balance sheet, and cash flow statement - as well as their interpretation.

Overall, students found the material of the course “useful” which included “many business terms and concepts for the future.” Students expressed that the real focus of the class was on the construction and application of financial statements. 

Professor Armstrong seemed to be somewhat polarizing in his teaching approach. Many students thought he did a great job at d,elivering a traditionally dull subject and several cited him as the best professor they had had at Wharton. On the other hand, while Armstrong seemed to be engaging in class, many students were frustrated with his lack of approachability. 

Students found the PowerPoint slides from lectures much more helpful than the textbook but appreciated practice problems and practice midterms posted on Webcafé. The course was “well-suited” for Wharton students but students felt that, for others, the class would be a “difficult challenge.” Students also expressed frustration with the curve.

Topics covered in ACCT 603 include the double-entry accounting system, accounting for common transactions, and income statement and balance sheet preparation.

Students commented that the class provided a “solid foundation and comprehensive framework” for financial accounting. Content was vanilla and expected, but students thought Bushee did a terrific job.

Bushee received ecstatic reviews from students. They ap,preciated Bushee’s intimate knowledge of the subject and were very enthusiastic about his creative ways to engage students with accounting, such as the Battle of the Cohorts. 

Students had little to say about the amount of work and quality of readings and assignments, but many did comment that the class was very accommodating to students who had little background in accounting prior to the class.

Accounting 743 studies how complex financial structures account for their activities. Primary emphasis is on the application of purchase accounting for mergers and acquisitions, the equity method for investments, and preparing and interpreting consolidated financial statements. Other topics covered include translations and re-measurements for nondomestic investments, and earnings per share calculations for complex financial structures. Tax considerations and acquisition strategies are of only peripheral interest in this class, and students who are concerned primarily with those topics are advised to seek a different elective. 

Students commented that this cours,e is extremely difficult and requires a great deal of work but will allow you to learn “a definitive skill set you can take away from Wharton.” The concepts are challenging and tend to be very technical and detailed. Students discourage anyone from taking the course if they are not strongly committed. Furthermore, students say that a lot of the course focuses on the preparation of consolidated financial statements rather than the interpretation of financial information. 

Professor Verrecchia received many mixed reviews. Students agree that he is very knowledgeable and demands hard work. Some comment that he is extremely stimulating and cares a lot about his students. Others note that he is “simply disinterested in student development” and does not convey the subject matter in an effective manner. 

A common note regarding this class is that it may “require 5-10 hours of prep per week.” Grades are based on 5 quizzes that are not too difficult but have very high means, causing a tight grade distribution. The course material is potentially useful for investors, investment bankers, and those going into M&A work, and is meant mainly for MBA students.

This course is an introduction to the basic concepts and standards underlying financial accounting systems. Several important concepts will be studied in detail, including: revenue recognition, inventory, long-lived assets, present value, and long term liabilities. The course emphasizes the construction of the basic financial accounting statements - the income statement, balance sheet, and cash flow statement - as well as their interpretation.   While most students supported the view of accounting as generally a “rather boring” subject, many agreed that Professor Reis made the best of it. According to one reviewer, the, professor “turned accounting into a stimulating topic by bringing in real firms and teaching how the financial documents are used.” Others echoed these sentiments; one student wrote that Professor Reis “showed us the meaning behind the numbers through live examples in a way that made me want to go to class.”   Reviews of Professor Reis were largely positive; he was described as “engaging,” “very personable,” and, according to one student, “one of the most dedicated and caring professors I have had at Penn.” The professor was almost uniformly lauded for his “engaging” teaching style and his willingness to work with students outside of class in office hours, during lunches, or even via Skype.   Students were nevertheless divided in their opinions of the course’s difficulty and grading scale. While one reviewer wrote that “Professor Reis was the most fair professor I have ever had at Penn,” another commented that the grading curve was “pretty harsh,” and a third student hoped that the professor might “reevaluate how reasonable the tests are.”

This course emphasizes the use of accounting information for internal planning and control purposes, as opposed to the external disclosure focus of financial accounting. Students will first learn alternative methods of preparing managerial accounting information in the first part of this course, and will spend the remainder of the course examining how these methods are used by companies. Managerial accounting is a company’s internal language, and is used for decision-making, production management, product design and pricing, performance evaluation, and motivating employees. Well-designed managerial accounting systems maximize economic profits (all relevant benefits minus all relevant costs). Course readings come from one textbook (Horngren, Datar, Foster, Rajan, and Ittner Cost Accounting: A Managerial Emphasis, 13th Edition, Prentice-Hall, Inc., 2009). Grading for this course is based upon a weighted average of three exams, the last of which counts as the final.   Students found this course to be “challenging, but not too difficult” as well as “overall worthwhile.” Students further agreed that this course proved to be informative and is “a great study of the concepts of managerial accounting.” However, students commented that the course material itself was sometimes “dry”, “boring”, and not practical, but the exams were more difficult than the material covered in class. The exams were often not “representative of the lecture slides or the recitation materials.”   Overall, students reported that Professor Defeo is a “great” lecturer who expresses “a lot of enthusiasm” and is always available and “wonderful at making sure that students understand the material.” Students agreed that Professor Defeo “cares a lot about his students and communicates the material very well.” By being “funny” and engaging, Professor Defeo makes the subject matter “as least boring as possible.”   Students overwhelmingly agreed that they wish there had been quizzes, homework, and problem sets dispersed throughout the semester rather than “big midterms” and a final that determined their grade entirely. Students felt that weekly “homework assignments or projects incorporated into the grading” would “ease some of the pressure off of the exams” and ensure that students “actually learned the materials, instead of trying to cram” right before the exams. Overall, “the content was manageable” though difficult around exam time.

Several important concepts will be studied in detail, including: revenue recognition, inventory, long-lived assets, present value, and long term liabilities. The course emphasizes the construction of the basic fi,nancial accounting statements - the income statement, balance sheet, and cash flow statement - as well as their interpretation.   While most students supported the view of accounting as generally a “rather boring” subject, many agreed that Professor Reis made the best of it. While one reviewer wrote that “Professor Reis was the most fair professor I have ever had at Penn,” another commented that the grading curve was ,“pretty harsh,” and a third student hoped that the professor might “reevaluate how reasonable the tests are.”

Overall, students agreed that this course was “useful” and “well-structured”, though often boring. Despite lectures that “were not particularly stimulating”, students acknowledged that the lecture was a “core class” and a requirement for business students. Many students commented that the lecture material coincided entirely with the assigned textbook readings. 

Students appreciated Professor Balakrishnan’s enthusiasm for the course material, accessibility to students seeking help, and overall ability to clearly communicate the subject matter. Students further praised Professor Balak,rishnan’s organization and “helpful” lecture slides. One student called Professor Balakrishnan an “excellent professor”. Another student commented that Professor Balakrishnan “spends classroom time on seemingly unimportant and easy concepts while going quickly through what is hard and important.” Overall, however, students agreed that Professor Balakrishnan presented the lecture material in a coherent and organized way that made it easier to understand, as well as engaging “through interesting examples and real world applications of concepts.”

Many of the students in this course complained that, though the material was not especially difficult, the course “requires a lot of work.” Students agreed that while the homework was fair, the exams were “tough.” Students disliked the multiple-choice format of the exams, as they felt the tests did not accurately assess student comprehension. Students commented that they would have appreciated a “more appropriate exam format” for “math-based classes” like this one.

Accounting 101 focuses on teaching the student to learn to read, understand, and analyze financial statements. The course adopts a decision-maker perspective of accounting by emphasizing the relation between accounting data and the underlying economic events that generated them. The course focuses initially on how to record economic events in the accounting records (i.e., bookkeeping and accrual accounting) and how to prepare and interpret the primary financial statements that summarize a firm's economic transactions (i.e., the balance sheet, the income statement, and the statement of cash flows). The course then examines in depth the major asset, long-term liability, and shareholder,s' equity accounts. 

Many students thought that the course was “boring,” but an equal number remarked that the real-life examples used in the class kept them engaged in the material. Students agreed that the material was very “relevant” to their future careers.

Students found Professor Balakrishnan to be a great lecturer who did a good job conveying the material through “humorous examples.” Students enjoyed Professor Balakrishnan’s “enthusiasm” and also remarked that he was readily available to meet outside of class.

Many students criticized the multiple-choice exam format and the “harsh curve,” but they also agreed that the exams closely paralleled what was taught in class. The course is intended for students with no previous exposure to financial accounting. It is part of the core requirements in Wharton.

Almost all students liked Professor Taylor. Accounting 102 is a two-part course in which the first half presents alternative methods of preparing mana,gerial accounting information, and the remainder of the course examines how companies use these methods. Managerial accounting is a company's internal language, and is used for decision-making, production management, product design and pricing and for motivating and evaluating employees. Unless you understand managerial accounting, you cannot have a thorough understanding of a company's internal operations.  What is taught in this course will provide the students with an understanding of the operations of future employers, enable students to be more successful at their jobs, and help students understand other companies they will encounter in their role as competitor, consultant, or investor.

Students said the course was somewhat interesting.  One thought it “should not be in the core,” but most found the course well structured and effective because of the professor. Another student felt the course focused “more on economics than accounting.” 

Students found Professor Gonedes “a very fair, reasonable, and fun professor.”  Many said he was personable and always available for extra help or discussion.  He was dubbed a “cool guy” and many appreciated that he kept classes short. He spent most of the class time explaining problems, which students felt was “a very wise and pragmatic way to teach accou,nting.”

There were 6 quizzes that occurred every other week in order to “make sure you keep on top of the material.”  The class grade “is given directly from an average of the exams.” In order to be exempt from the final, you must get an A on all 6 exams. Many felt the best way to learn in the class was to read the book before class to ask specific questions about problems. This class is part of the Wharton core.

Unless one understands managerial accounting, one cannot have a thorough understanding of a company's internal operations. What students learn in this course will help them understand the operations of their future employers, enabling them to be more successful at their jobs, and help them understand other companies they encounter in their role as competitor, consultant, or investor.

Many students felt that the material in this course was “useful,” although a number also noted that it w,as “boring.” Generally, students found the lector slides to be “helpful.”

Most students had high praise for Professor Defeo. In particular, many students highlighted how much “he truly cares about his students and goes out of his way to get to know every student and to help every student succeed.”  In particular, students noted that he was “very willing to talk” and was “very accessible.” They appreciated that he would “greet students from the class when he saw them around campus.”  Several students described Professor Defeo as “wordy and verbose,” but the majority felt that he “explained the material very clearly” and was “very thorough.” 

This course is part of the Wharton core and does not have any prerequisites.  A couple of students wished that the class included graded assignments so that final grades were based on more than exams. A few other students noted that the questions on the exams “did not always correspond to the material.”  Most students, however, did not comment on the difficulty of the course or the exams.

*Accounting 411 examines the concepts and procedures for, preparing financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. It focuses on the recording process, problems of periodic income measures and valuation, and statement presentation and analysis for companies formed as corporations.

The course had a lot of material to cover in one semester.  Some students acknowledged that it was challenging, but were glad they took it.  One said it was “very helpful and enjoyable.” Another student mentioned that the class covered many “concepts in one semester” and emphasized the need for students to keep up with the course.

Students had mixed reviews about Professor DeProphetis.  Some said she was “kind, a good teacher, and took questions willingly,” while others said “she was unsuitable to teach international students because she lacks the patience and will to make concepts understandable to them.”  One student said not to rely on the professor to explain all of the concepts in the “best or most understandable manner.”  Some felt her teaching style was detrimental because she “limited herself to reading only the information she had on her notes and did not explain the concepts in detail.”

One student said the homework took “about six hours per week.”  Many felt they learned more from the book than an,ything else because there was no feedback provided from the sessions.  Some students said the “practice exams were nothing like the actual exam” and expressed confusion about what was going to be on the exam.

values.c,omments:
The first part of ACCT 102 presents alternative methods of preparing managerial accounting information, and the remainder of the course examines how these methods are used by companies. Managerial accounting is a company's internal language and is used for decision-making, production management, product design and pricing and for motivating and evaluating employees. Unless you understand managerial accounting, you cannot have a thorough understanding of a company's internal operations. What students learn in this course will help them to understand the operations of their future employers (and enable them to be more successful at their jobs), and help them to understand other companies they encounter in their roles as competitors, consultants, or investors.

Some students felt that the material in ACCT 102 was “useful” and that they “[learned] a lot.”  However, others complained that its focus on manufacturing, its failure to “teach any analytical or technical skills beyond solving basic algebraic word problems,” and its overlap with other classes in the Wharton core made it “lack relevance to future classes or students’ careers.”  Students also generally agreed that the material was “quite dry” and that the class “[could] drag on.”

Students generally felt that Pro,fessor Defeo was “excellent.”  He “earnestly tried to engage students and assembled detailed lecture slides that were very useful study tools.”  As a result, many students praised Professor Defeo for “making the class [both] engaging and easy to understand.”  Several students also appreciated that Professor Defeo “[was] very accessible” and “a really nice and sincere guy.” Another student enjoyed the “frequent review sessions” that Professor Defeo would hold, in addition to regular office hours.

The course grade in ACCT 102 is based on two midterms and a final.  ACCT 102 has no prerequisites and is part of the Wharton core.

Described as “funny” and “engaging," Professor Heinle had positive reviews. Students appreciated his willingness to “discuss materials outside of class.” Professor Heinle goes “through materials very quickly, but he is still thorough.”

This class is a part of the Wharton core and required for all Wharton undergraduates.

Accounting 897, Taxes and Business Strategy, aims to develop a framework for understanding how taxes affect business decisions. Traditional finance and strategy courses do not consider the role of taxes. Similarly, traditional tax courses often ignore the richness of the decision context in which tax factors operate. They key themes of the framework- all parties, all taxes, and all costs- are applied to decision contexts such as investments, compensation, organizational form, regulated industries, financial instruments, tax-she,ltered investments, mergers and acquisitions, multinational, and multistate. The ultimate goal is to provide a new approach to thinking about taxes (and all forms of government intervention) that will be valuable even as laws and governments change. 
	Overall, students commented that this course was “great,” and although difficult, it was “extremely useful information.” Some student even commented that this class was “one of the best they took at Wharton.” The course offered “a great overview of corporate tax issues.” The information was “practical” “challenging” and “relevant.”
	Students regarded Professor Blouin as “fantastic” and knowledgeable about the course material. One student commented, “she knows the material cold, uses great examples to get her point across and is able to capture interest.” Another student complimented Professor Blouin’s ability to “[take] a fairly dry topic and [teach] it with such enthusiasm and interesting examples.”
	This is an MBA Course and auditors need permission.
